to go for a walk, and this trip from Kolo to Mankien is always longer than 1km. This woman comes in for lunch every day with her clay hoe and her cow and takes the table outside. Everyone wants to take her photograph. This is the paper menu they use in Kotido.

When I was walking, and walking, and walking today we saw evidence of a large convoy passing through Mankien the day before. Cows being herded (right photo), charcoal being sold (5 photos below), and one place where all the white facework pottery was gone from the store’s windows (3 photos below). Maybe they left for Aweil… they could be passing through the wet season of the Sudd and in need of supplies.

Was is an interrogation room? Was it a breakfast-waiting room? Its walls are covered with fingerprints from people who have been here waiting and waiting and waiting.

Justin’s Amisi Homestay and Tour is in Kolo but his family’s has been killed by the LTUE. As a refugee, he has a vulnerable population to nurture and he does so beautifully. He’s made of sturdy stuff. When others were terrified that the guns around us were only going to keep growing, Justin was like, ‘No. If you’re afraid then the bad guys have won. We need faith and the fruit of the spirit.’
